                <div type="apparatus">
               <listApp>
                 <app loc="1">
                  <lem>-ṣa<unclear reason="eccentric-ductus">c-cha</unclear>tā<choice><orig><unclear>p</unclear></orig><reg>b</reg></choice>de</lem>
                  <note>The shape of <foreign>ccha</foreign> is extremely eccentric. It seems that the scribe first engraved <foreign>cha</foreign> on the line and then added <foreign>c</foreign> on top of it as an afterthought and with a shape that is easily confused as a vowel marker <foreign>i</foreign>.</note>
                 </app>
                 <app loc="1">
                   <lem>muninā s<unclear cert="low">u</unclear>liṅga<unclear>m·</unclear></lem>
                   <rdg source="bib:Coedes1937-1966_01">munināsa liṅgaṁ</rdg>
                   <note>Cœdès' assumption of a verb form <foreign>āsa</foreign> here seems unsatisfactory. In the context, <foreign>suliṅgam</foreign> would be suitable, as shown by parallels in contemporary inscriptions (<ref target="K0077.xml">K. 77</ref>, st. III and <ref target="K0582.xml">K. 582</ref>, st. I), and we adopt this reading even though it is rather uncertain that a vowel marker <foreign>u</foreign> was actually engraved below the <foreign>s</foreign>.</note>
                 </app>
                 <app loc="2">
                    <lem>śrī-prabhāsomeśvaraḥ</lem>
                    <note>We tentatively assume that the hypermetrical <foreign>śrī-</foreign> was not intended to be part of the verse. Another way to resolve the metrical irregularity would be to correct <foreign>some</foreign> to <foreign>se</foreign>. The name <foreign>prabhāseśvara</foreign> is found in some contemporary Campā inscriptions (<ref target="C0081.xml">C. 81</ref>, face C, l. 2; <ref target="C0087.xml">C. 87</ref>, st. II; and three times in <ref target="C0096.xml">C. 96</ref>).</note>
                 </app>
                 <app loc="2">
                   <lem>liṅgarū<choice><sic>pam i</sic><corr>pa I</corr></choice>ha</lem>
                   <note>We assume that the author meant <foreign>liṅgarūpa iha saṁjñayā</foreign> and that proper meter can be obtained by applying secondary sandhi (<foreign>liṅgarūpeha saṁjñayā</foreign>) instead of the hiatus bridging <foreign>m</foreign> that we actually find.</note>
                 </app>
                 <app loc="2">
                    <lem>maṅgalaṁ</lem>
                    <note>Or read <foreign>maṅgala</foreign> without <foreign>anusvāra</foreign> and understand <foreign>maṅgala sthāpito</foreign> as <foreign>maṅgalaḥ sthāpito</foreign>?</note>
                 </app>
               </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
          <p rend="stanza" n="1">In the <supplied reason="subaudible">Śaka</supplied> year six hundred and nine, when Pisces <supplied reason="explanation">or Capricorn?</supplied> was in the ascendant, under <supplied reason="explanation">lunar mansion</supplied> Tiṣya, during the third night of the waxing <supplied reason="subaudible">fortnight</supplied> of Āṣāḍha, this beautiful <foreign>liṅga</foreign> has been duly erected by the sage called Vidyāvaravindu.</p>
            <p rend="stanza" n="2">May he, the illustrious Śrī Prabhāsomeśvara by name, standing here on earth in the form of a <foreign>liṅga</foreign>, award you happiness <supplied reason="subaudible">and</supplied> bliss!</p>
           </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="fra" source="bib:Coedes1937-1966_01">
          <p rend="stanza" n="1">Les Poissons étant à l'horizon, en l'année 609, <supplied reason="explanation">maison lunaire</supplied> Tiṣya, la troisième nuit de la lune croissante d'Āṣāḍha, ce <foreign>liṅga</foreign> a été érigé suivant les rites par le muni nommé Vidyāvaravindu.</p>
            <p rend="stanza" n="2">Puisse ce bienheureux Śrīprabhāsomeśvara, image du <foreign>liṅga</foreign>, placé ici sur la terre avec discernement, te donner bonheur et félicité.</p>
           </div>
           <!-- from K0652.text
           Traduction : L’ascendant dans le Capricorne, en l’an six-cent neuf, en Tiṣya, la troisième nuit du mois clair / sombre d’AAṣāḍha, le sage appelé Vidyāvaravindu a installé, selon la règle, cet [objet] avec un liṅga.
           Puisse ce bienheureux "Srīprabhāsomeśvara, image du liṅga, placé ici sur la terre avec discernement, te donner bonheur et félicité.
           % 687 A.D.
           Remarques :
           - La position de la Lune dans la mansion lunaire Tiṣya = Puṣya exclut que sita° représente, par sandhi (tiṣye asita° > tiṣye sita°), la quinzaine sombre (asita).
          -->
           <!-- Dominic's email 2021-01-09:
No ideas about jyotiṣa, I'm sorry to say.  I notice that the Billard/Eade 2006 article also favours śuklapakṣa for this inscription (see BEFEO 93, p. 402).
As for jhaṣendra as makara, of course it is equally possible.
I am not really convinced by suliṅgam. I can't see it.
The un-Pāṇinian verb form āsa has parallels in epic and one celebrated instance in the Kumārasambhava,
so it seems not inconceivable, and that damaged letter looks more like a sa to me.
The metrical issues are surprising.  Of course the hypermetrical first pāda can be regularised by assuming that the initial honorific śrī- is not intended to be part of the verse.
As for the second pāda, my guess is that the lapicide, who seems not too comfortable with some writing conventions (particularly regarding the vowels i and ī), intended to write liṅgarūpaṁ hi saṃjñayā (the hi being merely emphatic rather than causal).
 -->
         <div type="commentary">
            <p n="2" rend="stanza">Unusual metrical irregularities affect the first hemistich and go along with the irregular placement of <foreign>visarga</foreign> inside the curl of <foreign>śri</foreign> while the expected sandhi would be <foreign>śśri</foreign>.</p>
            <!-- <p>La position de la Lune dans la mansion lunaire Tiṣya = Puṣya exclut que <foreign>sita°</foreign> représente, par <foreign>sandhi</foreign> <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tiṣye asita°</foreign> > <foreign>tiṣye sita°</foreign></supplied>, la quinzaine sombre <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>asita</foreign></supplied>.</p> -->
         </div>
